  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or other criminal activities) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to disguise the origin of the money so it can be used without being traced back to illegal activities.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Similar laws exist globally, such as the **Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA)** in the UK and the **Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Directive** in the European Union. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset seizure, and imprisonment.\n\nGovernments and financial institutions have implemented strict anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and prevent such activities, including reporting suspicious transactions and verifying the identities of customers.",
